<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong may lift Canadian beef ban after granting mad cow all clear
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
HONG KONG, Nov 28 (AFP)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong's health chief indicated Sunday he would consider lifting a
ban on imports of Canadian beef imposed last year after the discovery
of mad cow disease in the top beef-producing province of Alberta.
</P>
<P>
Health secretary York Chow said officials had visited Canada and
given its farms the all clear on bovine spongiform encephalopathy
(BSE), or mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
"I think that we are a lot more satisfied with the situation there so
that we can make some decisions in the future," Chow said.
</P>
<P>
Canada last May confirmed a case of mad cow disease in Alberta.
</P>
<P>
BSE is a brain-wasting illness linked to the fatal variant
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (vCJD) in humans.
</P>
